#function that displays the OR, CI and p-values from a logistic model
get.OR2<-function(my.mod, names.var=NULL){
  my.coef <- summary(my.mod)$coef
  tmp<-cbind(exp(my.coef[,1]), exp(my.coef[,1]-qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]),  exp(my.coef[,1]+qnorm(.975)*my.coef[,2]), my.coef[,4])
  dimnames(tmp)[[2]]<-c("OR", "95\\% CI LL",  "95\\% CI UL", "P-value")
  if(!is.null(names.var))   dimnames(tmp)[[1]]<-names.var else dimnames(tmp)[[1]] <- dimnames(my.coef)[[1]]
  tmp
}

1 Research question and statistical analysis plan

Primary aim: Identify the risk factors for depression at first interview (cross-sectional), with special emphasis on the effect of age and how it differs between men and women and in different European geographical regions.

Secondary aim: Identify how the individual depressive symptoms of the euroD depression score are associated with the risk factors.

Data: Data from first SHARE interview.

Outcome variable: Presence of depression is defined as 4 or more points in the EURO-D questionnaire;

  • Result from EURO-D questionnaire

    • score (gv_health:eurod)

    • dicotomized euroD (gv_health:eurodcat)

Exclusion criteria:

  • SHARELIFE interview (Wave 3 or SHARELIFE in Wave 7 (technical_variables:mn103_, answer: Yes))

  • presence of dementia or other serious mental impairments (ph:ph006d16, Alzheimer’s disease, dementia, organic brain syndrome, senility or any other serious memory impairment) at current interview or at any previous interview. As the variable was first introduced in wave 2, the participants that reported the condition in wave 2 were removed also from wave 1.

  • age at first interview less than 50 at inclusion or unknown year of birth (all the interviews are removed)

  • age at first interview more than 90 at inclusion

  • subject with all missing values in the outcome variable eurod; for the cross-sectional part of the study: remove also those that having missing outcome at first measurement.

Independent predictors

A pivotal variable is a covariate that is considered to be strongly related with the outcome. This helps structure initial data analyses.

  1. age (cv_r:age_int) - pivotal variable,

  2. gender (cv_r:gender) - pivotal variable,

  3. country (cv_r:country) - pivotal variable, countries were categorized in European regions (Northern Europe (Denmark and Sweden), Western Europe (Austria, Germany, France, the Netherlands, Switzerland, Belgium, Ireland and Luxembourg), Southern Europe (Spain, Italy, Greece, Portugal and Israel) and Eastern Europe (Czech Republic, Poland, Hungary, Slovenia, Estonia and Croatia).

  4. education (gv_isced:isced1997_r) - to be further categorized in low (ISCED 1,2), medium (3,4), high(>=5), other (still in school, Other); new variable name: education

  5. presence of important chronic disease in 3 categories (having ever being diagnosed with 0, 1, or 2 or more out of 6of the following diseases: heart attack (ph:ph006d1), high blood pressure (ph:ph006d2), stroke (ph:ph006d4), diabetes (ph:ph006d5), cancer (ph:ph006d10) ), lung (ph:ph006d6, combined with ph:ph006d7 in wave 1 and 2); new variable name: dis_chronic_pres

  6. BMI (gv_health:bmi)

  7. physical activity (br:br015_): Sports or activities that are vigorous (4 categories)

  8. smoking (gv_health:cusmoke), reported being a smoker at baseline/first interview.

  9. living arrangement -> with partner/alone derived from dn:dn014_, to be transformed into married/with partner (“with partner”), widowed, separated, living alone (“alone”); note that also the dn:dn014_ variable (Change in marital status) must be taken into the account when creating the new variable, as in longitudinal interviews the marital status is recorded only if some changes occurred.

  10. Instrumental Activities of Daily Living (gv_health:IADL2, dicotomized version of the index)

Additional variables to download for further data cleaning/checking

  • weight (ph:ph012_)

  • height (ph:ph013_)

  • questionnaire version (technical_variables:mn101_, baseline or longitudinal).

  • sharelife interview (technical_variables:mn103_, only in wave 7)

  • For smoking status in br module:

    • br001_ (ever smoked daily for at least a year),
    • br002_ (smokes at present time - asked only if positive answer to br001_),

  • Single items that compose the EURO-D score form the gv_health module

    1. eurod1 depressed mood
    2. eurod2 pessimism
    3. eurod3 wishing death
    4. eurod4 guilt
    5. eurod5 sleep
    6. eurod6 interest
    7. eurod7 irritability
    8. eurod8 appetite
    9. eurod9 fatigue
    10. eurod10 concentration
    11. eurod11 enjoyment
    12. eurod12 tearfulness

  • Information about interview from cv_r module: - int_year (year of interview), - int_month (month of interview), - firstwave (first wave when included), - mobirth (month of birth), - yrbirth (year of birth)

  • Mental health history from mh module:

    • mh018_: ever suffering from depression for more than 14 days
    • mh019_: age at first diagnosis of depression
    • mh020_: ever treated for depression
    • mh021_: ever admitted to hospital because of depression

Statistical methods

A logistic regression model will be used to investigate the association between the risk factors and depression. The shape of the association between age and the probability of depression will be investigated with restricted cubic splines and compared to models with a linear effect of age. Two-way interactions between age, region of residence, and gender will be included in all models (“unadjusted analysis”), and models with additional risk factors will be considered (“adjusted analysis”).

The secondary research question is to analyze the single items that constitute the euroD score; the secondary analyses and results are described in Part 3.

2 Initial data analysis

The purpose of initial data analysis (IDA) is to study data properties that might impact the statistical modeling. We split this into three parts, missing, data, univariate and multivariate analyses.

2.1 Missing data

Overall, the number of missing values was low.

Outcome was missing for n=2147 participants (2 %). The characteristics of these participants were compared to those of participants with complete outcome value.

Missing outcome was more common in males, in older, less educated, less physically active, with more comorbidities and iadl limitations, living with a partner, non-smokers. Also, wave 6 had more missing values, while overall the Northern region had fewer missing values.

To investigate the predictors of missing outcome we fitted univiariate and multivariate logistic regression models, using the covariates from the research question.

After adjustment for the other covariates, a missing outcome was more common in males, in the 80+ age group, for the least physically active, with IADL limitations, living with a partner, non-smokers, from non-Northern regions. The association with chronic diseases was not present after adjusting for the other covariates, the association with education was also attenuated.

share.data.first.interview.model %>%
  dplyr::select(gender, region, cusmoke_imp, iadl2, living_arrangement) %>%
  dplyr::mutate_all(forcats::as_factor) %>%   
  dplyr::mutate_all(forcats::fct_explicit_na, "NA") %>%
  tidyr::pivot_longer(
    dplyr::everything(),
    names_to = "var",
    values_to = "value",
    values_drop_na = FALSE
  ) %>%
  dplyr::group_by(var, value) %>%
  dplyr::summarize(N = n()) %>%
  dplyr::mutate(
    freq = N / sum(N),
    pct = round((freq * 100), 1),
    axis_lab = paste0(value, ' ', '(N = ', N, ')'),
    var_label = case_when(var == "gender" ~ "Gender",
                          var == "cusmoke_imp" ~ "Current smoking",
                          var == "iadl2" ~ "IADL limitations",
                          var == "living_arrangement" ~ "Living arrangement", 
                          var == "region" ~ "Region"
                          )
  ) %>%
  ggplot(aes(
    x = reorder(axis_lab, pct),
    y = pct,
    label = pct
  )) +
  geom_text(nudge_y = 7) +
  geom_pointrange(aes(ymin = 0, ymax = pct), alpha = 1, size = 1, color = "grey") +
  geom_point(color = "firebrick2",
             alpha = 0.6,
             size = 3) +
  ylab("Percentage (%)") +
  scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0, 100)) +
  labs(caption = "Number of subjects with a non-missing value reported in brackets.\nNA = missing") +
  facet_wrap(~ var_label, ncol = 1, scales = "free_y") +
  coord_flip() +
  theme_minimal(base_size = 12) +
  theme(axis.title.y = element_blank(),
        panel.grid.minor = element_blank())

The age distribution was similar across regions and genders. Overall, females had lower education, lived alone more often, had less physical activity, smoked less often, had slightly less chronic diseases but more iadl limitations, depression was more common. The differences between genders were less pronounced in the Northern region. Regions differed in some aspects: education was substantially lower in Southern region, where living alone and vigorous activity were less common. Comorbidities and iadl limitations were more common in Easter region, vigorous physical activity and higher education in Northern region.

3.2 Results of data analysis

In the models the country effect were coded using the deviance coding - the coefficients estimate the difference between the mean of the country minus the grand mean. With the following code we define some variables that will be used for modeling, and define reference values for some categorical variables.

#using sum/deviance coding for the country variable, the meaning of the coefficient is the mean of the country minus the grand mean
 mat <- contr.sum(length(levels(share.data.first.interview$country)))
colnames(mat)  <- levels(share.data.first.interview$country)[-length(levels(share.data.first.interview$country))]
contrasts(share.data.first.interview$country) <- mat

#data transformations to enhance the readability of the outputs
share.data.first.interview$age_int_10 <- share.data.first.interview$age_int/10
share.data.first.interview$bmi_imp_10 <- share.data.first.interview$bmi_imp/10
share.data.first.interview$height_10 <- share.data.first.interview$height/10


#education, reference High

#pa_vig, reference More than once a week
share.data.first.interview$pa_vig <- factor(share.data.first.interview$pa_vig, levels = c("More than once a week", "Once a week", "One to three times a month",  "Hardly ever, or never") )

3.3 Model fitting

We considered two types of logistic models

  • unadjusted models: including two-way interactions between age, gender and geographic region (unadjusted models);
  • adjusted models: in addition to age, gender, and region as in the “unadjusted models” further adjusting by known risk factors (education, BMI, smoking, presence of chronic disease, vigorous physical activity, living arrangement).

Age was centered at 50 years and modeled - as a linear effect - as a non-linear effect with restricted cubic splines (rcs) and 5 knots placed at ages: 51, 56, 62, 70 and 81, using the default choice for the quantiles.

In the adjusted models the estimated probabilities were obtained using fixed levels of the risk factors (modal value for categorical covariates: non-smokers, low education, without chronic diseases, vigorous PA hardly ever, living with partner, and using median gender-specific BMI (25.9 for women and 26.6 for men).

#definition of standardized age for ease of interpretation of the coefficients
share.data.first.interview<- share.data.first.interview.model %>% mutate (age_int_stand = age_int - 50)

The geographic region was modeled - by grouping the countries in four regions (Northern, Western, Southern, Eastern)

Some of the coefficients of the estimated model are difficult to interpret, due to the use of restricted cubic splines and of interactions. Therefore, graphical displays of the estimated probabilities are used to present the results, rather than a table with the estimated coefficients. When RCS are used, the estimated coefficients/odds ratios (OR) are not presented only age and its interactions.

The purpose of modeling the linear effect of age is to evaluate the impact of the choice of functional forms on the estimated probability of depression.

3.3.1 Models with geographic regions

3.3.1.1 Unadjusted model with rcs for age

my.mod <- glm(eurodcat_imp ~ rcs(age_int_stand) + gender + region + 
                       rcs(age_int_stand):region + rcs(age_int_stand):gender + gender:region ,  
                                             data=share.data.first.interview, family="binomial",  x=TRUE, y=TRUE)

#save the spline terms in the complete data set for further use

                                                                    age2 = my.mod$x[,3],
                                                                    age3 = my.mod$x[,4],
                                                                    age4 = my.mod$x[,5])
    

# retrieve the location of knots used and assign them to Knots variable

#reproduces the spline values for age, expands for each integer value from 50 to 90
age = rcspline.eval(c(50:90)-50, knots=Knots)
age <- cbind.data.frame(age1=c(50:90)-50, age )
dimnames(age)[[2]] <- c("age1", "age2", "age3", "age4")






if(!is.null(my.mod$na.action)){

The regions differ mostly in the shape of the association between age and depression between ages 50 and 70, after 70 the probability of depression seems to increase in all regions. In Northern/Western countries the probability of depression slightly decreases between 50 and 70. In Southern countries the probability of depression increases at all considered ages, more sharply after 70, in Eastern countries there is an increase followed by a decrease shortly after 50 (a peak around 55).

At all ages and in all regions women had larger probability of depression; the interaction between gender and age was included in the model but there was little evidence that the interaction was significant (both from ANOVA and looking at the shape of the estimated age-gender specific probabilities); only in Southern region we noticed that the increase in probability of depression in older ages was sharper for men than for women.

For the risk factors: the adjusted model estimated a higher probability of depression for the participants with lower education, with chronic diseases, living alone, that did not engage in vigorous physical activity and for current smokers.

The adjustment for the risk factors changed the estimated shape of the association between age and probability of depression. In Northern and Western regions the probability decreased more markedly between 50 and 70, while the increase after 70 was smaller compared to the unadjusted analysis. In the Southern region the probability remained stable between 50 and 70 and increased afterwards. In the Eastern region the decrease between ages 55 and 65 was more marked, while the following increase was less pronounced. Overall, the adjusted analysis indicated that probability of depression decreased with age between 50 and 70 (except than in the Southern region, where it remained stable, in the Eastern region the increase started at about 65) and increased afterwards.

Also after adjustment, women had considerably higher probability of depression in all regions and at all ages.

After adjustment the interaction term between age and gender appeared as important, as men were estimated as having larger increase in probability of depression compared to women after 70 (statistically significant after the adjustment, P=0.0025).

The following graph helps visualizing the difference in the age effect between genders.

3.3.1.2.1 Estimated OR for depression for the comparison of selected ages (by country and gender)

The estimates from the model were further summarized reporting the OR estimated comparing selected ages (50, 60, 70, 80, 90) in different countries and within genders. These estimates, together with the graphs presented above, facilitate the understanding of the estimated model as the coefficients estimated for the cubic splines cannot be interpreted straightforwardly.

For example: OR_60vs50 is the estimated odds ratio (OR) for depression estimated from the model, comparing 60 year old with 50 year old (by country and gender). OR below (above) 1 indicate that the older age category has lower (higher) probability of depression compared to the younger age category.

#creates the figures subdirectory if it does not exist
if (!file.exists("figures")) dir.create("figures") 
pred.age.cat <- pred.age_all %>% filter(age1==0 | age1==10 | age1==20 | age1==30 | age1==40) %>% group_by(gender, region, model) %>% arrange(age1) %>% summarise(p_50=fit[1], p_60=fit[2], p_70=fit[3], p_80=fit[4], p_90=fit[5], 
                                                                                                                                                           OR_60v50=(p_60/(1-p_60))/(p_50/(1-p_50)),                                                                                                     OR_70v60=(p_70/(1-p_70))/(p_60/(1-p_60)),                                                                                                     OR_80v70=(p_80/(1-p_80))/(p_70/(1-p_70)),                                                                                       
            OR_90v80=(p_90/(1-p_90))/(p_80/(1-p_80))
                                                                                                                                                           ) %>% arrange(region, gender)

pred.age.cat.melt <- melt(pred.age.cat, id.vars=c("gender", "region", "model"), measure.vars=c("OR_60v50",  "OR_70v60", "OR_80v70", "OR_90v80"))

pred.age.cat.melt <- pred.age.cat.melt  %>% mutate(model=factor(model, levels=c("Unadjusted \n rcs", "Adjusted \n rcs")))

pred.age.cat.unadjusted <- pred.age.cat.melt 

ggplot(pred.age.cat.melt, aes(variable, value, color=gender)) + geom_point() + facet_grid(region~model)+

Within countries, the OR estimated for men and women comparing the same age categories were very similar in the unadjusted analysis, despite the presence of all the two-way interactions between age, gender and country. In the adjusted analysis the differences between genders appeared when we evaluated the effect of age after 70, where for men there was a larger increase in OR compared to women.

The OR were >1 after 70, below 1 for Nordic and Western region until 70.

pred.age_all$model <- factor(pred.age_all$model, levels = c("Unadjusted \n rcs", "Adjusted \n rcs",

                                                            "Adjusted \n linear age"))


ggplot(pred.age_all, aes(age1+50, fit, color=gender)) + geom_line() + facet_grid(model~region) + labs(x="Age", y="Estimated probability of depression") + scale_color_manual(values=c("#4699dd","#ff3db7" )) + ggtitle("Model comparisons") + 
  geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = fit - 1.96*se.fit, ymax = fit + 1.96*se.fit), alpha = 0.2, linetype=0) +  theme_bw()

#comparison of adjusted/unadjusted
pred.age_all %>% filter(model=="Unadjusted \n rcs" | model=="Adjusted \n rcs") %>% droplevels() %>% ggplot(aes(age1+50, fit, color=gender)) + geom_line() + facet_grid(model~region) + labs(x="Age", y="Estimated probability of depression") + scale_color_manual(values=c("#4699dd","#ff3db7" )) + ggtitle("Comparison of estimated probabilities") + 
       geom_ribbon(aes(ymin = fit - 1.96*se.fit, ymax = fit + 1.96*se.fit), alpha = 0.2, linetype=0) +  theme_bw()  

ggsave("FigDepression_ModComparison_rcsOnly.tiff", device="tiff", path = "figures" , compression ="lzw")


ggsave("FigDepression_ModComparison_rcsOnly.png", device="png", path = "figures" , scale=.6)

As expected, the model with linear age effect would not have captured the non-linear association between age and probability of depression. For example, for the Northern region the unadjusted analysis would have suggested that there was no association between age and depression, while the adjusted analysis would have suggested a negative association.
